<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-347-842  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 347 842.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 16 1990 v24 n16 p104(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Training in the executive suite; senior-level management needs IStraining too - but in its own way. (information systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Russell, M.L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>High-level business executives need information systems (IS)training so they can render sound decisions influencing theircompany's future rather than relying on input from non-objectivevendors and internal advisors.andP;  IS training organizations need tomake sure that they cover all important and pertinent topics withthe correct amount of detail required for these executives.andO;Topics that should be included are the selection of new systems,developing strategies for information management, monitoringdevelopment projects, managing investments in software anddevising disaster recovery plans.andP;  Training materials should bedesigned as reference tools rather than student guides.andP;  Follow-upis a critical aspect to training executives in IS and shouldinclude sending the executives recent IS articles, books and othermaterials of possible interest to them.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Training of EmployeesExecutive.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>